Here is the terraform script for creating a vpc, both Public Subnet & Private SubNet in different Availability Zones (AZ). This will be done using AWS' Terraform provider. Please replace `your_access_key` and `your_secret_key` with your actual access key ID and secret Access Key:
```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region     = "us-west-2" # Replace this to the desired AZ in AWS (e.g., us-east-1, eu-central-1 etc.)
  access_key = "your_access_key"  
  secret_key  = "your_secret_key"   
}
data "aws_caller_identity" "current" {} # This will give you the account id of your AWS user. You can use it to set up IAM roles and policies for S3, EC2 etc in Terraform scripts 
variable "vpc_cidr" { default = "10.0.0.0/16"}   // Replace this with desired CIDR (e.g., '172.16.0.0/16') for VPC and Subnets in AWS 
variable "public_subnet_cidr" { default = "10.0.1.0/24"} // Replace this with desired CIDR (e.g., '172.31.58.96/27') for Public Subnets in AWS 
variable "private_subnet_cidr" { default = "10.0.2.0/24"} // Replace this with desired CIDR (e.g., '172.31.58.64/29') for Private Subnets in AWS 
resource "aws_vpc" "main" {   # This will create a VPC on your behalf and return the ID of that vpc, which you can use to identify this resource later (e.g., ${aws_vpc.main.id})   
 cidr_block = var.vpc_cidr  // Replace with desired CIDR for main VPC in AWS  
}
resource "aws_subnet" "public" { # This will create a public subnets on your behalf and return the ID of that SubNet, which you can use to identify this resource later (e.g., ${aws_vpc.main}/${var.public_subnet_cidr})
  vpc_id     = aws_vpc.main.id   # Replace with your VPC ID from above   
  cidr_block = var.public_subnet_cidr //Replaces the CIDR for Public Subnets in AWS (e.g., '172.31.58.96/24')   # Replace with desired public subnet's CIDR
  tags =  {
    Name = "public-subnet" // Add more Tags as per requirement, e.g.: environment=prod; region=${var.region} etc...    
 }
}
resource "aws_subnet" "private1" { # This will create a private subnets on your behalf and return the ID of that SubNet  (e.g., ${aws_vpc.main}/${var.public_subnet_cidr})   // Replace with desired CIDR for Private-SubNets in AWS
 vpc_id     = aws_vpc.main.id    #Replaces the VPC ID from above  (e.g., $aws_vpc.main)     
 cidr_block  = var.private_subnet_cidr // Replace with desired private subnets' CIDR in AWS  
 tags =  {     Name = "Private-SubNet"    }// Add more Tags as per requirement, e.g.: environment=prod; region=${var.region} etc... 
}
resource "aws_subnet" "private2" { // This will create a private subnets on your behalf and return the ID of that SubNet (e.g., ${aws_vpc.main}/${var.public_subnet_cidr})   // Replace with desired CIDR for Private-SubNets in AWS
 vpc_id     = aws_vpc.main.id    //Replaces the VPC ID from above  (e.g., $aws_vpc.main)     
 cidr_block  = var.private_subnet

Here is a simple example using the `aws_alb` and `aws_autoscaling` providers in Terraform to create such infrastructure as per your requirement, but please note that you need appropriate permissions for AWS services. 
```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-west-2" # replace with the desired aws location (e.g., us-east-1)
}
data "aws_caller_identity" "current" {}
variable "vpc_id" ""   //replace this value by your VPC ID in AWS 
variaible "subnet_ids" []    // replace with the list of subnets you want to use for Auto Scaling Group. e.g., ["Subnet-1a2b3c4d","Subetm-5f6h7i8j"]  
variable "security_group_id" ""  //replace this value by your Security group ID in AWS   
resource "aws_autoscaling_group" "example" {
  availability_zones = ["us-west-2a", "us-west-2b","us-west-2c"]   # replace with the desired zones (e.g., us-east, eu-central) in AWS region   
  desired_capacity = 3     //replace this value by your Auto Scaling Group Desired Capacity     
  max_size        = 5       //replace this value as Max Size of EC2 instances  
  min_size       =1          // replace with the minimum number of ec2 instance required in auto scaling group. e,g., if you want to start only when there are one user active then set it equal or greater than two   
}
resource "aws_elb" "example" {   #replace this value by your Load Balancer name  and other parameters as per requirement (e.g.: target group ids, security groups)    
  availability_zones = ["us-west-2a", "us-west-2b","us-west-2c"]    // replace with the desired zones in AWS region  
  name               = var.loadbalancerName      #replace this value by your Load Balance Name and other parameters as per requirement (e,g., load balancing scheme)    
}
```
This is a very basic example of how you can set up an Auto Scaling Group with AWS Application LoadBalancers in Terraform using the `aws_autoscaling` provider. You would need to replace placeholders like "us-west-2", zones, VPC IDs and other parameters as per your requirements (e.,g.: load balancer name).
